{"title_page": "PM CARES Fund", "text_new": "\n\nThe '''Prime Minister's Citizen Assistance and Relief in Emergency Situations Fund''' '''(PM CARES Fund)''' was created on 28 March 2020 following the [[COVID-19 pandemic in India]]. The fund will be used for combating, containment and relief efforts against the coronavirus outbreak and similar pandemic like situations in the future. The [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister]] is the chairman of the trust. Members will include the defence, home and finance ministers.it is however not clear whether it is a government trust or it can be used as a private trust by the memBers of the trust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-cares-pm-narendra-modi-announces-new-covid-19-fund-gets-rs-25-crore-from-akshay-kumar-2202275|title=PM Modi Announces New COVID-19 Fund, Gets Rs 25 Crore From Akshay Kumar|last=|first=|date=|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=384047|title=People urged to donate generously in PM CARES fund; PM Modi says every contribution matters|website=newsonair.com|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.cm/article/current-affairs/pm-narendra-modi-announces-pm-cares-fund-to-fight-coronavirus-outbreak-120032900031_1.html|title=PM Narendra Modi announces PM-CARES fund to fight coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-29|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live|others=PTI}}</ref>\n\nThe fund will also enable [[micro-donation]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharma|first=Sandhya|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/internet/cyber-chiefs-warning-as-hackers-target-pms-covid-fund/articleshow/74877953.cms|title=Cyber chief's warning as hackers target PM's Covid fund|date=2020-03-29|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The minimum donation accepted for the PM CARES Fund is {{INRConvert|10||lk=yes|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":3\" /> The donations will be tax exempt and fall under [[corporate social responsibility]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/policy/donation-to-pm-cares-fund-to-be-fully-exempted-under-income-tax-act/article31221733.ece|title=Donation to PM CARES Fund to be fully exempted section 80G of I-T Act|last=|first=|date=31 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The Prime Minister had said that the [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|PMO]] had received many requests to help in the war against COVID-19. Accordingly, the fund was set up and will be used for disaster management and research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dqindia.com/pm-cares-fund-need-know/|title=PM CARES Fund: All You Need to Know|date=2020-03-30|website=DATAQUEST|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-announces-emergency-relief-fund-for-coronavirus-fight/articleshow/74863297.cms|title=PM Modi announces emergency relief fund for coronavirus fight|date=2020-03-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== About ==\nAny contribution made to the PM CARES Fund before 30 June would qualify for a [[tax exemption]] under (80G) [[The Income-tax Act, 1961|Income Tax Act, 1961]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Noronha|first=Gaurav|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/govt-clarifies-on-companys-contributions-to-pm-cares-fund-above-csr-limit/articleshow/74907220.cms|title=Govt clarifies on company's contributions to PM CARES Fund above CSR limit|date=2020-03-31|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ordinance-issued-to-make-pm-cares-donations-tax-free/articleshow/74923420.cms|title=Ordinance issued to make PM CARES donations tax free|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]] announced that contributions to the PM CARES fund would be counted as part of the companies corporate social responsibility with additional CSR being offset in subsequent years.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe PM CARES fund is different from the [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]] (PMNRF), which was created in 1948 and has been used by the [[Government of India]] ever since, for example during the recent [[2013 North India floods]], the [[2015 South India floods]] and the [[2019 Kerala floods]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmindia.gov.in/en/pms-funds/|title=PM National Relief Fund {{!}} Prime Minister of India|website=www.pmindia.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the creation of the fund opposition members raised a queries as to why a separate fund was needed, when it was registered, under which act and why it did not contain any members of civil society or opposition as part of the trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-questions-setting-up-of-pm-cares-fund-to-deal-with-coronavirus/article31210904.ece|title=Congress questions setting up of PM CARES Fund to deal with coronavirus|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 7th April 2020, after the PM CARES fund raised 6500 Crores for relief on Covid-19, Congress head Sonia Gandhi asked PM Narendra Modi to transfer all the money to the PMNRF.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transfer-all-money-under-pm-cares-to-pmnrf-sonia-gandhi/articleshow/75036589.cms|title=Transfer all money under PM-Cares to PMNRF: Sonia Gandhi|date=2020-04-07|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> many of peoples are also asking why another fund is made when thee is already one established by our first pm mr javahar lal nehru in 1948 its also an directly funded directly by the peoples of our nation. go government fund is been used for this. and another question has been raised about is why there is no opposition party member or a judicial official has been included because this fund has collected 6500 crores in just one week and its a huge amount so if there is no one to moniter the ruling party can use this for their own benefits. obiously this need a opposition  party member who can moniter the money been spent on what and which place. so ya this is a big question right now\n\n\n[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]] reported that government sources justified creation of the fund saying that PMNRF is mainly for natural disasters, while PM CARES Fund is for COVID-19 similar pandemic situations.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/pm-cares-fund-better-suited-tto-deal-with-coronavirus-crisis-say-legal-experts/story/399670.html|title=PM CARES Fund better suited to deal with coronavirus crisis, say legal experts|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was also mentioned that the [[Consolidated Fund of India]] needs legislative jurisdiction to be used; creation of a fund like the PM CARES Fund takes care of legislative hurdles.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nImmediately after the fund was created a number of fake accounts popped up. While the original [[Unified Payments Interface|UPI]] accounts were pmcares@sbi and pmcares@iob . [[Delhi Police]] booked an individual for creating a UPI account removing the 's' called pmcare@sbi, intended to scam people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/delhi-police-books-fraudsters-for-making-fake-sbi-account-of-pm-s-covid-19-relief-fund-1661272-2020-03-30|title=Delhi Police books fraudsters for making fake SBI account of PM's Covid-19 Relief Fund|last=Ojha|first=Arvind|date=30 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Government schemes in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi]]\n", "text_old": "\n\nThe '''Prime Minister's Citizen Assistance and Relief in Emergency Situations Fund''' '''(PM CARES Fund)''' was created on 28 March 2020 following the [[COVID-19 pandemic in India]]. The fund will be used for combating, containment and relief efforts against the coronavirus outbreak and similar pandemic like situations in the future. The [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister]] is the chairman of the trust. Members will include the defence, home and finance ministers.it is however not clear whether it is a government trust or it can be used as a private trust by the memBers of the trust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-cares-pm-narendra-modi-announces-new-covid-19-fund-gets-rs-25-crore-from-akshay-kumar-2202275|title=PM Modi Announces New COVID-19 Fund, Gets Rs 25 Crore From Akshay Kumar|last=|first=|date=|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=384047|title=People urged to donate generously in PM CARES fund; PM Modi says every contribution matters|website=newsonair.com|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.cm/article/current-affairs/pm-narendra-modi-announces-pm-cares-fund-to-fight-coronavirus-outbreak-120032900031_1.html|title=PM Narendra Modi announces PM-CARES fund to fight coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-29|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live|others=PTI}}</ref>\n\nThe fund will also enable [[micro-donation]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharma|first=Sandhya|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/internet/cyber-chiefs-warning-as-hackers-target-pms-covid-fund/articleshow/74877953.cms|title=Cyber chief's warning as hackers target PM's Covid fund|date=2020-03-29|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The minimum donation accepted for the PM CARES Fund is {{INRConvert|10||lk=yes|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":3\" /> The donations will be tax exempt and fall under [[corporate social responsibility]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/policy/donation-to-pm-cares-fund-to-be-fully-exempted-under-income-tax-act/article31221733.ece|title=Donation to PM CARES Fund to be fully exempted section 80G of I-T Act|last=|first=|date=31 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The Prime Minister had said that the [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|PMO]] had received many requests to help in the war against COVID-19. Accordingly, the fund was set up and will be used for disaster management and research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dqindia.com/pm-cares-fund-need-know/|title=PM CARES Fund: All You Need to Know|date=2020-03-30|website=DATAQUEST|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-announces-emergency-relief-fund-for-coronavirus-fight/articleshow/74863297.cms|title=PM Modi announces emergency relief fund for coronavirus fight|date=2020-03-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== About ==\nAny contribution made to the PM CARES Fund before 30 June would qualify for a [[tax exemption]] under (80G) [[The Income-tax Act, 1961|Income Tax Act, 1961]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Noronha|first=Gaurav|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/govt-clarifies-on-companys-contributions-to-pm-cares-fund-above-csr-limit/articleshow/74907220.cms|title=Govt clarifies on company's contributions to PM CARES Fund above CSR limit|date=2020-03-31|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ordinance-issued-to-make-pm-cares-donations-tax-free/articleshow/74923420.cms|title=Ordinance issued to make PM CARES donations tax free|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]] announced that contributions to the PM CARES fund would be counted as part of the companies corporate social responsibility with additional CSR being offset in subsequent years.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe PM CARES fund is different from the [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]] (PMNRF), which was created in 1948 and has been used by the [[Government of India]] ever since, for example during the recent [[2013 North India floods]], the [[2015 South India floods]] and the [[2019 Kerala floods]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmindia.gov.in/en/pms-funds/|title=PM National Relief Fund {{!}} Prime Minister of India|website=www.pmindia.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the creation of the fund opposition members raised a queries as to why a separate fund was needed, when it was registered, under which act and why it did not contain any members of civil society or opposition as part of the trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-questions-setting-up-of-pm-cares-fund-to-deal-with-coronavirus/article31210904.ece|title=Congress questions setting up of PM CARES Fund to deal with coronavirus|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 7th April 2020, after the PM CARES fund raised 6500 Crores for relief on Covid-19, Congress head Sonia Gandhi asked PM Narendra Modi to transfer all the money to the PMNRF.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transfer-all-money-under-pm-cares-to-pmnrf-sonia-gandhi/articleshow/75036589.cms|title=Transfer all money under PM-Cares to PMNRF: Sonia Gandhi|date=2020-04-07|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]] reported that government sources justified creation of the fund saying that PMNRF is mainly for natural disasters, while PM CARES Fund is for COVID-19 similar pandemic situations.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/pm-cares-fund-better-suited-tto-deal-with-coronavirus-crisis-say-legal-experts/story/399670.html|title=PM CARES Fund better suited to deal with coronavirus crisis, say legal experts|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was also mentioned that the [[Consolidated Fund of India]] needs legislative jurisdiction to be used; creation of a fund like the PM CARES Fund takes care of legislative hurdles.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nImmediately after the fund was created a number of fake accounts popped up. While the original [[Unified Payments Interface|UPI]] accounts were pmcares@sbi and pmcares@iob . [[Delhi Police]] booked an individual for creating a UPI account removing the 's' called pmcare@sbi, intended to scam people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/delhi-police-books-fraudsters-for-making-fake-sbi-account-of-pm-s-covid-19-relief-fund-1661272-2020-03-30|title=Delhi Police books fraudsters for making fake SBI account of PM's Covid-19 Relief Fund|last=Ojha|first=Arvind|date=30 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Government schemes in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi]]\n", "name_user": "Rishabhshivi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAbout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PM_CARES_Fund"}
{"title_page": "Sea Warrior Creek", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Sea Warrior Creek''' is a [[stream]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alabama]].<ref name=\"GNIS\">{{GNIS|153356|name=Sea Warrior Creek}}</ref>\n\n\"Sea Warrior\" is the result of a name corrupted from the [[Choctaw language]] (''Isawaya''<ref name=GNIS />) purported to mean \"crouching deer\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Baca|first=Keith A.|title=Native American Place Names in Mississippi|url=https://epdf.pub/native-american-place-names-in-mississippi.html|year=2007|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-483-6|page=93}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Alabama]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Choctaw County, Alabama]]\n\n\n{{Alabama-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sea Warrior Creek''' is a [[stream]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alabama]].<ref name=\"GNIS\">{{GNIS|153356|name=Sea Warrior Creek}}</ref>\n\n\"Sea Warrior\" is the result of a name corrupted from the [[Choctaw language]] (''Isawaya''<ref name=GNIS />) purported to mean \"crouching deer\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Baca|first=Keith A.|title=Native American Place Names in Mississippi|url=https://epdf.pub/native-american-place-names-in-mississippi.html|year=2007|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-483-6|page=93}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Alabama]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Choctaw County, Alabama]]\n\n{{Alabama-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_Warrior_Creek"}
{"title_page": "Inga-Stina Robson, Baroness Robson of Kiddington", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Robson of Kiddington\n|image            = Stina_Robson.jpg\n|caption          = Stina Robson\n|office           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start       = 14 May 1974\n|term_end         = 9 February 1999<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1919|08|20|df=y}}\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1999|02|09|1919|08|20|df=y}}\n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|alma_mater       = \n}}\n\n'''Inga-Stina Robson, Baroness Robson of Kiddington''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Arvidsson'''; 20 August 1919 \u2013 9 February 1999), often known as '''Stina Robson''', was an [[England|Anglo]]-[[Sweden|Swedish]] political activist.\n\nBorn to a wealthy family in [[Stockholm]] as Inga-Stina Arvidsson, she attended \u00d6linska Girls' School before becoming a secretary in the Swedish [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]]' office in [[London]], where she met [[Lawrence Robson]], an accountant, and the two married in 1940.  During [[World War II]], she worked as a translator for the British [[Ministry of Information (UK)|Ministry of Information]].<ref name=\"sutherland\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/92376 Inga-Stina Robson profile] by Duncan Sutherland, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''; accessed 20 March 2014.</ref>\n\nRobson settled at [[Kiddington Hall]] near [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire]], and worked on her husband's unsuccessful candidature for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] in [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]] at the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 general election]].  Their house was used as a conference centre and was popular for Liberal Party events.  In the run-up to the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], Lawrence was the Liberals' prospective candidate in [[Eye (UK Parliament constituency)|Eye]], but he was appointed to a government commission and withdrew, leaving Inga-Stina to fight the seat, although she was not successful. Later the same year, she became a [[magistrate]].<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nRobson stood again in Eye at the [[1959 United Kingdom general election|1959 general election]], then in [[Gloucester (UK Parliament constituency)|Gloucester]] in [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] and [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966]]. Although she never came close to election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]], she was elected to [[Chipping Norton, Oxfordshire|Chipping Norton]] [[Rural District Council]].<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nIn 1968, Robson became President of the [[Women's Liberal Federation]], standing down in 1970 when she was elected President of the Liberal Party.  As president, she opposed [[radicalism (politics)|radicalism]] and, in particular, the policies advocated by the [[National League of Young Liberals]].  She was created  '''Baroness Robson of Kiddington''', of [[Kiddington]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]] on 14 May 1974,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=46292 |date=17 May 1974 |page=6033}}</ref> becoming the Liberals' spokesperson on agriculture and the environment in the [[House of Lords]]. In 1982, she succeeded her husband as Chair of the [[National Liberal Club]], and also as Chair of the [[Anglo-Swedish Society]]. She joined the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], successors of the Liberal Party, and in 1988, she chaired a panel investigating fraud in the [[European Union]]. She stood down as a magistrate in 1989, by which time she was the longest-serving magistrate in the country. In 1993, she became the party spokesperson on health.<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nLady Robson was the Chairman of the charity Attend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attend.org.uk/about-us/people-we-honour-0/attend-vips |title=VIPs |website=Attend.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> (then National Association of Leagues of Hospital Friends) from 1986\u20131994. When she retired in 1994, she was honored as Vice President; a position she would hold from 1995\u20131998.\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Or a Viking ship oars in action Sable between two fleurs-de-lys Azure.\n|supporters = Dexter a sea stag Argent attired and finned Or, sinister a sea horse also Arget crined and finned Or, the tails Proper and each gorged with a baron's coronet also Proper.<ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=1985}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title  = President of the [[Women's Liberal Federation]] | years = 1968\u20131970 | before = Gaenor Heathcote Amory | after = [[Penelope Jessel]]}}\n{{succession box | title  = [[President of the Liberal Party (UK)|President of the Liberal Party]] | years = 1970\u20131971 | before = [[Timothy Beaumont]] | after = [[Stephen Terrell]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robson of Kiddington, Inga-Stina Robson, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Liberal Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Swedish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Robson of Kiddington\n|image            = Stina_Robson.jpg\n|caption          = Stina Robson\n|office           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start       = 14 May 1974\n|term_end         = 9 February 1999<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1919|08|20|df=y}}\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1999|02|09|1919|08|20|df=y}}\n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|alma_mater       = \n}}\n\n'''Inga-Stina Robson, Baroness Robson of Kiddington''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Arvidsson'''; 20 August 1919 \u2013 9 February 1999), often known as '''Stina Robson''', was an [[England|Anglo]]-[[Sweden|Swedish]] political activist.\n\nBorn to a wealthy family in [[Stockholm]] as Inga-Stina Arvidsson, she attended \u00d6linska Girls' School before becoming a secretary in the Swedish [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]]' office in [[London]], where she met [[Lawrence Robson]], an accountant, and the two married in 1940.  During [[World War II]], she worked as a translator for the British [[Ministry of Information (UK)|Ministry of Information]].<ref name=\"sutherland\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/92376 Inga-Stina Robson profile] by Duncan Sutherland, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''; accessed 20 March 2014.</ref>\n\nRobson settled at [[Kiddington Hall]] near [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire]], and worked on her husband's unsuccessful candidature for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] in [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]] at the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 general election]].  Their house was used as a conference centre and was popular for Liberal Party events.  In the run-up to the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], Lawrence was the Liberals' prospective candidate in [[Eye (UK Parliament constituency)|Eye]], but he was appointed to a government commission and withdrew, leaving Inga-Stina to fight the seat, although she was not successful. Later the same year, she became a [[magistrate]].<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nRobson stood again in Eye at the [[1959 United Kingdom general election|1959 general election]], then in [[Gloucester (UK Parliament constituency)|Gloucester]] in [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] and [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966]]. Although she never came close to election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]], she was elected to [[Chipping Norton, Oxfordshire|Chipping Norton]] [[Rural District Council]].<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nIn 1968, Robson became President of the [[Women's Liberal Federation]], standing down in 1970 when she was elected President of the Liberal Party.  As president, she opposed [[radicalism (politics)|radicalism]] and, in particular, the policies advocated by the [[National League of Young Liberals]].  She was created  '''Baroness Robson of Kiddington''', of [[Kiddington]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]] on 14 May 1974,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=46292 |date=17 May 1974 |page=6033}}</ref> becoming the Liberals' spokesperson on agriculture and the environment in the [[House of Lords]]. In 1982, she succeeded her husband as Chair of the [[National Liberal Club]], and also as Chair of the [[Anglo-Swedish Society]]. She joined the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], successors of the Liberal Party, and in 1988, she chaired a panel investigating fraud in the [[European Union]]. She stood down as a magistrate in 1989, by which time she was the longest-serving magistrate in the country. In 1993, she became the party spokesperson on health.<ref name=\"sutherland\"/>\n\nLady Robson was the Chairman of the charity Attend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attend.org.uk/about-us/people-we-honour-0/attend-vips |title=VIPs |website=Attend.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> (then National Association of Leagues of Hospital Friends) from 1986-1994. When she retired in 1994, she was honored as Vice President; a position she would hold from 1995-1998.\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Or a Viking ship oars in action Sable between two fleurs-de-lys Azure.\n|supporters = Dexter a sea stag Argent attired and finned Or, sinister a sea horse also Arget crined and finned Or, the tails Proper and each gorged with a baron's coronet also Proper.<ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=1985}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title  = President of the [[Women's Liberal Federation]] | years = 1968\u20131970 | before = Gaenor Heathcote Amory | after = [[Penelope Jessel]]}}\n{{succession box | title  = [[President of the Liberal Party (UK)|President of the Liberal Party]] | years = 1970\u20131971 | before = [[Timothy Beaumont]] | after = [[Stephen Terrell]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robson of Kiddington, Inga-Stina Robson, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Liberal Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Swedish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1986-1994 \u2192 1986\u20131994 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inga-Stina_Robson,_Baroness_Robson_of_Kiddington"}
{"title_page": "Mukesh Bhakar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| 1blankname1      = [[Chief Minister of Rajasthan|Chief Minister]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Ashok Gehlot]]\n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2 = President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 7 April 2020\n| 1blankname2 = National President\n| 1namedata2 = [[Srinivas BV]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ashok Chandna]]\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]], he represents also in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref> As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan in 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| 1blankname1      = [[Chief Minister of Rajasthan|Chief Minister]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Ashok Gehlot]]\n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2 = President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 7 April 2020\n| 1blankname2 = National President\n| 1namedata2 = [[Srinivas BV]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ashok Chandna]]\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| profession       = [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]. He represents As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|ur