ws.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "name_user": "Mukesh Bhakar 0013", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mukesh_Bhakar"}
{"title_page": "Chris Rennard, Baron Rennard", "text_new": "{{COI|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| office1          = Chief Executive of the<br>[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Rennard\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image            = official portrait of Lord Rennard crop 2.jpg\n| term_start1      = 2003\n| term_end1        = 2009\n| predecessor1     = Andrew Ellis (1988 \u2013 1989)<br/>\nGraham Elson (1989 \u2013 1997) <br />\nElizabeth Pamplin (1998 \u2013 1999) <br />\nHugh Rickard (2000 \u2013 2003)\n| successor1       = [[Christopher Fox, Baron Fox|Chris Fox]]<br /> (2010 - 2011)<br />\nTim Gordon (2012 -)\n|birth_name=Christopher John Rennard\n|office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 21 July 1999<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1960|7|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Liverpool]], England\n| party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]<br />Independent <small>(January 2014-August 2014)</small>\n| alma_mater = [[University of Liverpool]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher John Rennard, Baron Rennard''', [[MBE]]<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url= http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-rennard/2484 |title= Lord Rennard|website=UK Parliament|publisher= |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> (born 8 July 1960<ref>{{cite web |author=Westminster Parliamentary Record |url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/peer/Christopher-Rennard/1622 |title=Westminster Parliamentary Record |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202114436/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/peer/Christopher-Rennard/1622 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) is a British life peer in the [[House of Lords]], appointed to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]' benches in 1999. He was Director of Campaigns & Elections for the Liberal Democrats from 1989 to 2003, and Chief Executive of the party from 2003 to 2009.\n\n==Education and early career==\nRennard was born in 1960 the second of three sons to Cecil Rennard (1888-1963) and Jean Winfred Watson (1923-1976/77). He has an older step sister from his father's first marriage, his father also had two step children through that marriage.<ref>Winning Here, Rennard, 2018, pages 3-4</ref>\n\nRennard was educated at the [[Liverpool Blue Coat School]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Hansard, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldhansrd/vo030109/text/30109-03.htm |title=House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings, 9th January 2003 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk}}</ref> and gained a BA (Hons) Social Studies in 1982 from the [[University of Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web |author=University of Liverpool |url=http://www.liv.ac.uk/events/event.php?event_id=27369&event_day_id=46250 |title=University of Liverpool Events, 6th July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140122204020/http://www.liv.ac.uk/events/event.php?event_id=27369&event_day_id=46250 |archivedate=22 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> From his early teens he was an active member of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] Party. He began his political activism in Liverpool in the late 1970s, where he chaired the Liverpool University Liberals. He cites the early pioneers of community politics in Liverpool, including [[Cyril Carr]], [[Trevor Jones (Liberal politician)|Trevor Jones]] and [[David Alton]], as having had a major influence on him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard, Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk/|accessdate=10 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> Rennard was Deputy Chair of the Liverpool Liberal Party and organised many of the party's election campaigns in the 1980s, at a time when the Liberal Party controlled the City Council. The first successful parliamentary by-election campaign he worked on was the [[1979 Liverpool Edge Hill by-election|Liverpool Edge Hill by-election]] in March 1979, at which the party's candidate was [[Lord Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]. Rennard was Alton's agent when he successfully contested the newly created [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]] constituency in 1983 (after boundary changes) and helped to secure an excellent result there in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|a general election]] that saw a landslide [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] victory nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard, Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|accessdate=10 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Iain Dale interview with Lord Rennard |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml |title=Iain Dale interview with Lord Rennard |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219181245/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml |archivedate=19 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In conversation with... Chris Rennard|url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml|website=www.totalpolitics.com|publisher=Total Politics|accessdate=10 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219181245/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml|archivedate=19 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984 he became one of the party's national Area Agents, based in [[Leicester]], when the party won its first seats there for over 20 years. He was a member of many of the Liberal/Alliance by-election campaign teams, including those in [[1986 West Derbyshire by-election|West Derbyshire in 1986]] and [[1987 Greenwich by-election|Greenwich in 1987]]. He was a member of the standing committee of ALC (Association of Liberal Councillors) and wrote some party publications on election campaigning and party organisation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Lord Rennard|url=http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=2340|website=www.liberal-international.org/|publisher=Liberal International|accessdate=10 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131122/http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=2340|archivedate=10 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==National positions==\nIn 1989 Rennard was appointed as Director of Campaigns and Elections for the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He married Ann McTegart<ref>{{cite web|author=The Peerage |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p31196.htm |title=The Peerage}}</ref> (whom he had met when they were both Liberal Party agents in Merseyside in the 1980s) and was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[1989 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51578 |date=31 December 1988 |page=15 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] he oversaw the party's target-seat campaign, which resulted in the Liberal Democrats nearly doubling its number of MPs from 26 to 46.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rennard and 50/50 hindsight|url=http://edinburgheye.wordpress.com/2014/01/27/rennard-and-5050-hindsight/|website=edinburgheye.wordpress.com|publisher=Edinburgh Eye|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=27 January 2014}}</ref> In 2001 and 2005, with Tim Razzall ([[Baron Razzall]]) as Campaign Chair and [[Charles Kennedy]] as Leader, he also directed the Liberal Democrats' general-election campaigns, which further increased the number of Lib Dem MPs respectively to 52 and 62, the largest total of Liberal or Liberal Democrat MPs since 1923.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Grady|first1=Sean|title=Chris Rennard: A Liberal Democrat who knows how to win elections|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-rennard-a-liberal-democrat-who-knows-how-to-win-elections-6271205.html|accessdate=18 November 2014|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rennard and 50/50 Hindsight|url=http://edinburgheye.wordpress.com/2014/01/27/rennard-and-5050-hindsight/|website=edinburgheye.wordpress.com|publisher=Edinburgh Eye|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was the party's Chief Executive between 2003 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-rennard/2484|website=www.parliament.uk/|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> During his employment by the Liberal Democrats at a national level, he was credited with winning 13 parliamentary by-elections for the party<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: low profile belied his influence on British politics|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/24/lord-rennard-lib-dems-profile|website=www.theguardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> (11 gains and 2 holds), out of a total of 74 by-elections held\u2014a success rate of 17.5%. The [[1990 Eastbourne by-election|Eastbourne by-election]] in 1990 was claimed by Rennard as rescuing the Liberal Democrats from their very weak position following the merger of the Liberal Party and the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]], and saw a 16,923 Conservative majority become a Liberal Democrat majority of 4,550.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|publisher=Lib dems|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> The by-election followed a major row between Rennard and [[Paddy Ashdown]] over the party leader's initial opposition to the Liberal Democrats fighting the by-election. A [[1993 Christchurch by-election|by-election in Christchurch during July 1993]] saw the Liberal Democrats gain the seat from the Conservatives by the largest swing (35%) against any British government since 1918.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/top-ten-lib-dem-breakthrough-moments/ |title=Top Ten Lib Dem 'breakthrough moments' |publisher=Epolitix.com |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512171830/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/top-ten-lib-dem-breakthrough-moments/ |archivedate=12 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|publisher=Lib Dems|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nFormer party leader Charles Kennedy has described Rennard as \"a quite extraordinary figure in British politics\", while his predecessor Paddy Ashdown praised Rennard as \"a formidable and widely-respected practitioner of political campaigning across all parties\".<ref>Paddy Ashdown, ''The Ashdown Diaries: Volume One, 1988-1997'' (Penguin, London, 2000) p.64</ref> [[Iain Dale]] said in an interview in ''[[Total Politics]]'' (June 2011) that Rennard \"is probably the most formidable and feared political campaigner of the last 20 years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.html |accessdate=14 June 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], [[Andrew Stunell]], a friend of Rennard's, is reported as having said: \"Last time people didn't follow Chris [Rennard's] instructions and the difference between those who did and who didn't&nbsp;\u2013 like in the [[Isle of Wight (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Wight]] [which the party lost]&nbsp;\u2013 was very clear. The message got through.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/08/uk.liberaldemocrats |author=Branigan, Tania |newspaper=The Guardian |location =London |date=8 April 2005 |title=Kennedy launches big push for 70-plus seats}}</ref>\n\nRennard has claimed credit for pioneering the successful Liberal Democrat election strategy of claiming narrow majorities when in second or even third place and ruthlessly squeezing third-party votes in Tory\u2013Lib Dem and Labour\u2013Lib Dem marginals; although this technique has been in use by the Liberal Party's campaigns teams since at least October 1974, when Rennard was 14 years old.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.markpack.org.uk/107519/first-tactical-voting-bar-chart-appear-political-leaflet/ |title = When did the first tactical voting bar chart appear on a political leaflet?|date = January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Later posts==\nRennard served as the Liberal Democrats Chief Executive from 2003 to 2009, during which time he was in overall charge of the party's election campaigns and organisation. His campaigns team continued to build the party's successes through by-elections such as [[2003 Brent East by-election|Brent East in 2003]] and [[2004 Leicester South by-election|Leicester South in 2004]]. Following the Lib Dems' victory at Brent East in 2003, ''[[The Independent]]'' profiled Lord Rennard, saying calling him \"a Liberal democrat who knows how to win elections\" and saying that \"In recent years thoughtful Conservatives surveying their wretched political predicament sometimes wondered aloud where \"their\" Peter Mandelson was. As usual they were asking the wrong question. They should have been seeking \"their\" Chris Rennard. For while Rennard enjoys a rather lower profile than New Labour's sultan of spin, the Liberal Democrats' own election guru is a no less formidable operator. True, Rennard has not managed to take the Liberal Democrats to Downing Street with a landslide majority, but it is in large part to him that the party owes its revival, the latest evidence of which was its victory in Brent East.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard: A Liberal Democrat who knows how to win elections|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-rennard-a-liberal-democrat-who-knows-how-to-win-elections-6271205.html|website=www.independent.co.uk|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=20 September 2003}}</ref> As Chief Executive, Rennard oversaw the party\u2019s recovery from a series of crises in January 2006 when Charles Kennedy resigned as Leader, [[Mark Oaten]] resigned as the party\u2019s Home Affairs spokesman and [[Simon Hughes]] was claimed to be gay by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper. This turbulent period came to an end in March when he oversaw victory in the [[2006 Dunfermline and West Fife by-election]], which brought the total of Liberal Democrats MPs to 63.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly Information Bulletin: 23rd May 2009|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmwib/wb090523/state.htm|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> He chaired the Liberal Democrat general election campaign for both Sir [[Menzies Campbell]] and [[Nick Clegg]] between summer 2006 and May 2009, when he stood down as Chief Executive of the Party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Lord Rennard|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21569997|accessdate=18 November 2014|work=BBC News|date=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRennard announced that he would be standing down as chief executive of the Liberal Democrats in May 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/home/chris-rennard%E2%80%99s-personal-letter-to-members-265015275;show |title=Chris Rennard Personal Letter to Members |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527142916/http://www.libdems.org.uk/home/chris-rennard%E2%80%99s-personal-letter-to-members-265015275%3Bshow |archivedate=27 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He indicated that he had discussed standing down some time earlier with the party leader, Nick Clegg, and that this was for family and health reasons, saying that he had \"struggled to maintain good [[Diabetes|diabetic control]] with the rigours of a very demanding lifestyle\". Clegg subsequently conceded that sexual harassment allegations against Rennard from multiple women also contributed to Rennard's resignation, stating that \"He left on health grounds but of course the issues of his inappropriate behaviour were in the background.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Lord Rennard did not resign purely on health grounds, Clegg admits|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/27/lord-rennard-health-nick-clegg|website=www.theguardian.com/|accessdate=11 November 2015}}{{cite web|title=Profile: Sex claims contributed to Lord Rennard's resignation from Lib Dems, says Nick Clegg|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9897096/Sex-claims-contributed-to-Lord-Rennards-resignation-from-Lib-Dems-says-Nick-Clegg.html|website=www.telegraph.co.uk/|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter relinquishing the full-time position, Rennard continued to contribute to some party election campaigns on a constituency-by-constituency basis. However, Lib Dem President and future Party Leader [[Tim Farron]] insisted that \"Under no circumstances\" would Rennard have a future campaigning role.<ref>{{cite web|title=No role for Rennard, Farron tells accuser|url=https://www.politicshome.com/party-politics/articles/story/no-role-rennard-farron-tells-accuser|website=www.politicshome.com/|accessdate=11 November 2015|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> Rennard was appointed to chair a Commission on the [[Big Society]] set up by the [[Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations]] (ACEVO) to articulate a civil society vision of what charities wanted to achieve through the Big Society agenda. He was formerly a trustee of the charity [[Action on Smoking and Health]] (ASH).\n\nHe is a Patron of The Crescent, a centre in [[St Albans]] which provides help and support to those living with, or otherwise affected by, [[HIV]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.thecrescent.org.uk/index.php/about/|website=www.thecrescent.org.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nLord Rennard provides advice and support on campaign, communication, fundraising and management issues through the consultancy Rennard & McTegart Ltd. He is the Director of Communications for the British Healthcare Trades Association (BHTA) and writes a regular \"Westminster Watch\" column for their Bulletin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Westminster Watch|url=http://www.bhta.net/westminsterwatch|website=www.bhta.net/|accessdate=18 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129052229/http://www.bhta.net/westminsterwatch|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nRennard was created a [[life peer]] on 21 July 1999 as Baron Rennard, of [[Wavertree]] in the [[Merseyside|County of Merseyside]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55564 |date=27 July 1999 |page=8076}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 27 July 1999.<ref>{{cite web|author=Minute Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/minutes/990727/ldminute.htm |title=House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings, 27 July 1999 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> He is the treasurer of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Diabetes and a vice chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Smoking and Health.{{fact|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn the House of Lords, Rennard has mostly spoken on political and constitutional reform issues. He led for the Liberal Democrats in debate on what became the [[Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000]], that set the framework for rules such as those governing party finance. He spoke in favour of replacing large donor funding of parties, with limited state funding. He has campaigned against abuses of the postal vote system and helped to bring about some reforms to it. He has spoken out strongly for and voted for [[reform of the House of Lords]] at every possible stage. In the 2010\u20132015 Parliament he was responsible for changing proposals to move electoral registration to an entirely voluntary system that some say would have greatly favoured the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile Chris Rennard|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> He was also responsible in the House of Lords for the cross-party amendment that blocked [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|the proposed review of parliamentary boundaries]], thought by some to favour the Conservatives by up to 30 seats at the next general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201213/ldhansrd/text/130114-0001.htm#1301145000174)|website=publications.parliament.uk|title= Hansard House of Lords Monday, 14 January 2013|publisher=Hansard|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> He also speaks in the Lords on other issues, including some associated with public health including diabetes and smoking.\n\n===Expenses===\nIn May 2009 Rennard was criticised for claiming a House of Lords member's allowance of \u00a341,678, having designated a flat in Eastbourne as his main residence and his central London house as his second home.<ref name=expenses>{{cite news|title= LDV Members' Survey \u2013 MPs' expenses (1): what you said about Chris Rennard |url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/ldv-members-survey-mps-expenses-1-what-you-said-about-chris-rennard-14901.html|work=[[Stephen Tall]]|publisher= Liberal Democrat Voice |date=21 May 2005}}</ref> A subsequent complaint made by the Sunlight Centre for Open Politics was investigated by the Clerk of the Parliaments [[Michael Pownall]], who did not uphold it, \"In view of the assurances by Lord Rennard about the change in his circumstances and the time he spends in Eastbourne, and in the absence of any definition of main address in the current guidance to the House of Lords\u2019 Members Expenses Scheme\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/upload/LordRennardcomplaint.pdf|title=Complaint against Lord Rennard|date=20 October 2009|website=www.parliament.uk|publisher=House of Lords|accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of sexual harassment==\nIn February 2013, ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' ran a report on Lord Rennard, alleging a history of sexual harassment during his time as an official of the party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Cathy|title=Lib Dems allegations of sexual impropriety  |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/lib-dem-allegations-of-sexual-impropriety|publisher=Channel 4 News / Firecrest Films |accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> Channel 4 stated that the alleged victims decided to comment publicly since Rennard had begun to again play an 'active role in the Party'.<ref name=activerole>{{cite news|title= Lord Rennard: why are we running the story now? |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/lord-rennard-why-are-we-running-the-story-now|accessdate=11 November 2015|work=[[Cathy Newman]]|publisher= Channel 4 News |date=25 February 2013}}</ref> He strongly denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Rennard issues fresh denial of sexual impropriety claims|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21543152|work=BBC News|date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest claims go back to 2007 when two women met [[Paul Burstow]], then the party's Chief Whip in the Commons, to raise the issue with him.<ref>Rowena Mason [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10116934/Nick-Clegg-admits-he-knew-of-Lord-Rennard-rumours-for-years.html \"Timelime of the Lord Rennard sexual harassment allegations\"], telegraph.co.uk, 12 June 2013</ref> In a February 2013 statement issued shortly after ''Channel 4 News'' had broken the story, Nick Clegg wrote that claims about the improper conduct of Lord Rennard had been brought to his attention in 2008, but Rennard had denied any wrongdoing when challenged.<ref name=\"C4240213\">[http://www.channel4.com/news/clegg-aware-of-concerns-about-lord-rennard \"Clegg aware of 'concerns' about Lord Rennard\"], ''Channel 4 News'', 24 February 2013</ref> The \"indirect and non-specific concerns\" he had been told about meant that he could take no further action,<ref name=\"C4240213\"/> but [[Danny Alexander]], Clegg's chief of staff at the time, had warned Rennard that the alleged behaviour would be \"wholly unacceptable\".<ref>Juliette Jowit and Steven Morris [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/24/nick-clegg-admits-rennard-concerns \"Nick Clegg admits he heard of Rennard 'concerns' in 2008\"], ''The Guardian'', 24 February 2013</ref> A subsequent independent report in June 2013 by Helena Morrissey into \"processes and culture within the Liberal Democrats\" said that the leadership should have held an inquiry into the allegations at that time (when Rennard was still a member of staff).<ref>Rowena Mason [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10116359/Nick-Clegg-admits-he-knew-of-Lord-Rennard-rumours-for-years.html \"Nick Clegg 'should have ordered Rennard sex harassment inquiry after 2008 warnings'\"], telegraph.co.uk, 12 June 2013</ref>\n\nThere was no such inquiry until that conducted by Alistair Webster QC, who concluded after examining over a hundred statements (including those made by the complainants as a result of interviews with specially trained police officers) that the evidence was insufficient to proceed to a disciplinary hearing. While staffing disciplinary matters would have required a civil standard of proof to be met, at that time Liberal Democrat regulations demanded a criminal standard of proof to uphold allegations against a Party member.\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police]] carried out their own investigation after one of the complainants went to them on 27 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1082051/met-police-formally-investigate-lord-rennard|title=Met Police Formally Investigate Lord Rennard|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 April 2013 |website=news.sky.com |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> On 26 September 2013 the Metropolitan Police announced they had dropped the investigation, because they had found \"insufficient evidence\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|title=Police drop Lord Rennard sexual misconduct inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/26/police-drop-lord-rennard-inquiry|accessdate=27 September 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 September 2013}}</ref> They did not submit a file to the Crown Prosecution Service for consideration.<ref>{{cite web|title=Police drop Lord Rennard sexual misconduct inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/26/police-drop-lord-rennard-inquiry|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the police \"No Further Action\" decision, the Liberal Democrats resumed their own inquiry with Alistair Webster QC acting as \"independent investigator.\" According to a later public statement by Lord Rennard, there were three complaints by the deadline of 22 November 2013, and Alistair Webster reported that there was insufficient evidence to proceed further.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: His statement in full|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lord-rennard-his-statement-in-full-9073125.html|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref> A fourth complaint was then also considered and Alistair Webster again reported (on 22 December 2013) that there was insufficient evidence to proceed any further. The party rules required the independent QC to either recommend a disciplinary hearing to investigate further, or to say that there was insufficient evidence to proceed.\n\nAlistair Webster informed Lord Rennard on 15 January 2014 that the decision was \"No Further Action\", and that the party statement that day was \"not his responsibility.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: Hos Statement in Full|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lord-rennard-his-statement-in-full-9073125.html|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref>  Webster's public statement on his conclusions from his report stated that there was \"broadly credible\" evidence of \"behaviour which violated the personal space and autonomy of the complainants.\"<ref name=Webster>{{cite news|title= Internal investigation into allegations against Lord Rennard |url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/internal-investigation-into-allegations-against-lord-rennard-37847.html| publisher= Lib Dem Voice |date=15 Jan 2014}}</ref> The question of the standard of proof required did not arise as the evidence was insufficient to hold a disciplinary hearing - except that Webster did consider this question, noting in his statement that \"my task was to review the evidence which I received and consider whether there was a greater than 50% chance that such a charge could be proved to the standard required by the rules, i.e. proof beyond reasonable doubt [a criminal, rather than civil standard of proof] ... My view, judging the evidence as a whole, is that there is a less than 50% chance that a charge against Lord Rennard could be proved to the requisite standard\". Webster concluded that it was \"unlikely that it could be established beyond reasonable doubt that Lord Rennard had intended to act in an indecent or sexually inappropriate way\" and that \"I have specifically discounted suggestions made during the investigation that the incidents had been invented as part of a political campaign against Lord Rennard. In my view Lord Rennard ought to reflect upon the effect that his behaviour has had and the distress which it caused and that an apology would be appropriate, as would a commitment to change his behaviour in future\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lib Dems will take no action against Lord Rennard over harassment claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jan/15/lord-rennard-lib-dems-no-action-sex-pest-complaints|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nNeither Nick Clegg nor Tim Farron had read the Webster report (Webster stated 'I do not consider it appropriate to publish the evidence') and Lord Rennard was initially also denied sight of it, in spite of earlier promises that he would see it.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard gets Lib Dem apology for botched disciplinary process|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/25/lord-rennard-lib-dem-apology-disciplinary-process|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Farron asked Lord Rennard to apologise to the women involved. It was reported in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that Clegg had stated that \"it is right that Chris Rennard has been asked in this report to apologise, to reflect on his behaviour.\" Clegg went on to state that Rennard would not be \"playing any role in my general election plans for the campaign in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=POLITICS: Lord Rennard allegations: Nick Clegg interview on independent report|url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist//ITN/2014/01/15/R15011408/?v=1|website=www.itnsource.com}}</ref>\n\nThe report was eventually provided to Lord Rennard and to the four complainants in March 2014 and it did not contain any request or recommendation for an apology [citation needed] - though Webster made this request in his Jan 2014 public statement on conclusions from his investigation.<ref name=\"Webster\"/> A statement from Lord Rennard in August 2014 said that a Liberal Democrat English Appeals Committee ruling in July 2014 found that \"I could not be criticised over my reaction to the previous report by Alistair Webster QC, as I was not given sight of the report for 11 weeks\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard's Liberal Democrat suspension is lifted|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-08-19/lord-rennard-statement-in-full/|website=www.itv.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2014, Rennard was suspended from the Liberal Democrats; he was informed that this was on the basis of \"Media and social media comments made by you, endorsed by you and made on your behalf that have attacked the party and the party processes publicly since the announcement of the Webster report results.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard Has Lib Dem Suspension Lifted|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/08/19/lord-rennard-has-lib-dem-suspension-lifted_n_5692668.html|website=www.huffingtonpost.co.uk}}</ref> Lord Rennard's friend and legal adviser, [[Lord Carlile of Berriew|Lord Carlile]], wrote a strongly critical article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' about \"the party's unjust and arbitrary conduct of the case\".<ref name=les>{{cite news|title=Former aide to Nick Clegg quits the Lib-Dems over Lord Rennard row|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/former-aide-to-nick-clegg-quits-the-libdems-over-lord-rennard-row-9070194.html|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|publisher=Evening Standard Ltd|date=19 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=beebunjust>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Victoria|title=Savile claims and royal 'job-share' - newspaper review|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-the-papers-25797931|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[BBC]]|date=19 January 2014}}</ref> The week following the suspension, ''[[The Times]]'' reported<ref name=cuban>{{cite news|title= Rennard could expose Lib Dem sex scandals |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article1367820.ece|accessdate=11 November 2015|work=[[The Times]]|publisher= Times Newspapers Limited |date=26 January 2014}}</ref> from 'allies' of Rennard that the peer knew \"where the bodies are buried\" and that were he expelled from the Liberal Democrats he would reveal two decades of sex scandal in the Party: \"We have had a [[Cuban missile crisis]] over the past week.\"\n\nLord Rennard issued a lengthy personal statement in response to his suspension explaining some of the background to the allegations made against him and the party's handling of them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard statement in full|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25814565|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe seven-month suspension of his party membership was lifted in August 2014, when there was a \"No Further Action\" decision in relation to his criticisms of party processes and he was restored to full membership of the party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard has suspension from Lib Dems lifted|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28858533|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref> A later statement was issued by Rennard on 21 August 2014 saying that:\n{{cquote|All allegations made about Lord Rennard have now been investigated thoroughly. This included a seven month investigation by specially trained officers of the Metropolitan Police. The police decided that there could be no charges and did not even a send a file to the Crown Prosecution Service. In addition, there was a lengthy investigation by independent QC Alistair Webster. He also concluded that there was insufficient evidence even to proceed to a disciplinary hearing. The Liberal Democrat Party has now dealt with all the allegations and the matter is closed. We must advise anyone against publishing or broadcasting defamatory remarks. Accusations that were rejected by both the Metropolitan Police and an independent QC would be treated as such.<ref name = \"LD Voice\">[http://libdemvoice.org/statement-from-lord-rennard-42120.html Statement from Lord Rennard Liberal Democrat Voice, 21 August 2014 Accessed 22 August 2014]</ref>}}\n\nHelena Morrissey was invited to report on processes and culture within the Liberal Democrats, and her report in December 2014 concluded, in relation to Lord Rennard, that:\n\n{{cquote|At this point, December 2014, every investigation has concluded with no further action to be taken against Lord Rennard. The process over the past nearly two years \u2013 conducted according to the prevailing rules \u2013 has run its course and although the outcome is a source of great frustration to some, I believe that the Party can only move on if that outcome is accepted. At this stage, given that the Party applied its own processes, there is no justification for it remaining ambivalent towards Lord Rennard \u2013 he should be just as welcome a participant or guest at Party events as any other.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morrissey|first1=Helena|title=Progress Report on the Processes and Culture of the Liberal Democrats|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/libdems/pages/7117/attachments/original/1418903950/M-report-part-2.pdf?1418903950|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>}} She also observed how the Party's burden of proof for disciplinary procedures had been lowered from a criminal ('beyond reasonable doubt') to a civil standard of proof ('on the balance of probabilities').\n\nDuring his campaign to become Liberal Democrat leader, Tim Farron said that if elected he would have \"no intention of appointing him [Rennard] to any role in the party.\"<ref name=farron>{{cite news|title= Rennard could expose Lib Dem sex scandals\n |url=http://www.markpack.org.uk/133285/what-role-would-rennard-have-under-a-new-lib-dem-leader/|work=[[Mark Pack]]|publisher= Mark Pack |date=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, the Party's Deputy Leader (and future Leader), [[Jo Swinson]], expressed her desire in a comment piece that Lord Rennard would not be a Liberal Democrat member, writing \"That Lord Rennard remains in the party, showing no remorse or contrition, while many of the women involved have left, fills me with sadness and anger ... I do not want Lord Rennard to continue as a member of the party. As far as I am concerned, he is not welcome.\"<ref name=SwinsonsaysRennardnotwelcome>{{cite news|title= Sexual harassment: a chance for change |url= https://medium.com/@jo_swinson/sexual-harassment-a-chance-for-change-1e87a9db1581| publisher= Medium |date=19 Nov 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attempt to join Liberal Democrat Federal Executive==\nIn November 2015 Rennard was chosen to serve as the Liberal Democrat Lords' representative to the Liberal Democrats' governing Federal Executive Committee. A Special Conference triggered by Party members opposed to the decision was averted when Rennard agreed to resign his Committee membership following a public intervention by Tim Farron, who stated \"Chris serving on the FE is not in our best interest, as the levels of anger and division have shown. I am therefore asking Chris to step down from the FE in the best interests of the party\".<ref name=Farronpubliccall>{{cite news|title= Tim Farron calls on Chris Rennard to step down from the Federal Executive |url= http://www.libdemvoice.org/breaking-tim-farron-calls-on-chris-rennard-to-step-down-from-the-federal-executive-48283.html| publisher= Lib Dem Voice |date=17 Nov 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Memoirs==\nThe first volume of his memoirs, ''Winning Here'', went on sale on 25 January 2018.<ref>Private Eye issue No 1463 - 9\u201322 February 2018 - Page 11 \"Comeuppance Corner\"</ref>\nThe launch was mired in controversy, when it turned out Lord Rennard was being investigated by the information commissioner for a breach of data protection law by sending unsolicited emails promoting the book to Lib Dem supporters. ''[[Private Eye]]'' reported that the email offered a 25% discount \"when you click through to the shopping page\". Readers who accepted would then be treated to how \"I started running council elections in my teens, was a successful constituent agent at 22, the Lib Dem director of campaigns and elections at 29, a peer at 39\". ''Private Eye'' titled the article \"Comeuppance Corner\", as Lord Rennard was one of those that voted for a change in the data protection law to make newspapers pay both sides' costs in data protection cases.<ref>Biteback Publishing (25 Jan. 2018) {{ISBN|1785903373}} {{ISBN|978-1785903373}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,,1263235,00.html Profile] From ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 2004.\n*Interview with Lord Rennard [https://web.archive.org/web/20120311174423/http://www.thirdsector.co.uk/News/Article/1052871/Interview-Lord-Rennard-chair-Acevos-Big-Society-Commission] From ''[[Third Sector (magazine)|Third Sector]]'' February 2011\n*Article on the AV Referendum [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/14/av-miliband-clegg] From ''[[The Guardian]]'' March 2011\n*In depth interview with Lord Rennard for ''Civil Society'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20110418065050/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/finance/indepth/interviews/content/8683/liberal_influence_andrew_hind_interviews_lord_rennard]\n*In conversation with Iain Dale for Total Politics [https://web.archive.org/web/20110613024904/http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml] June 2011\n*Lord Rennard's article about the Big Society [http://www.libdemvoice.org/chris-rennard-fill-in-the-blanks-of-the-big-society-24266.html] June 2011\n*The They Work For You website [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/lord_rennard]\n\n{{Current Liberal Democrat Peers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rennard, Chris}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Liverpool Blue Coat School]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| office1          = Chief Executive of the<br>[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Rennard\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image            = official portrait of Lord Rennard crop 2.jpg\n| term_start1      = 2003\n| term_end1        = 2009\n| predecessor1     = Andrew Ellis (1988 \u2013 1989)<br/>\nGraham Elson (1989 \u2013 1997) <br />\nElizabeth Pamplin (1998 \u2013 1999) <br />\nHugh Rickard (2000 \u2013 2003)\n| successor1       = [[Christopher Fox, Baron Fox|Chris Fox]]<br /> (2010 - 2011)<br />\nTim Gordon (2012 -)\n|birth_name=Christopher John Rennard\n|office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 21 July 1999<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1960|7|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Liverpool]], England\n| party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]<br />Independent <small>(January 2014-August 2014)</small>\n| alma_mater = [[University of Liverpool]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher John Rennard, Baron Rennard''', [[MBE]]<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url= http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-rennard/2484 |title= Lord Rennard|website=UK Parliament|publisher= |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> (born 8 July 1960<ref>{{cite web |author=Westminster Parliamentary Record |url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/peer/Christopher-Rennard/1622 |title=Westminster Parliamentary Record |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202114436/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/peer/Christopher-Rennard/1622 |archivedate=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) is a British life peer in the [[House of Lords]], appointed to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]' benches in 1999. He was Director of Campaigns & Elections for the Liberal Democrats from 1989 to 2003, and Chief Executive of the party from 2003 to 2009.\n\n==Education and early career==\nRennard was born in 1960 the second of three sons to Cecil Rennard (1888-1963) and Jean Winfred Watson (1923-1976/77). He has an older step sister from his father's first marriage, his father also had two step children through that marriage.<ref>Winning Here, Rennard, 2018, pages 3-4</ref>\n\nRennard was educated at the [[Liverpool Blue Coat School]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Hansard, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldhansrd/vo030109/text/30109-03.htm |title=House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings, 9th January 2003 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk}}</ref> and gained a BA (Hons) Social Studies in 1982 from the [[University of Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web |author=University of Liverpool |url=http://www.liv.ac.uk/events/event.php?event_id=27369&event_day_id=46250 |title=University of Liverpool Events, 6th July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140122204020/http://www.liv.ac.uk/events/event.php?event_id=27369&event_day_id=46250 |archivedate=22 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> From his early teens he was an active member of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] Party. He began his political activism in Liverpool in the late 1970s, where he chaired the Liverpool University Liberals. He cites the early pioneers of community politics in Liverpool, including [[Cyril Carr]], [[Trevor Jones (Liberal politician)|Trevor Jones]] and [[David Alton]], as having had a major influence on him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard, Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk/|accessdate=10 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> Rennard was Deputy Chair of the Liverpool Liberal Party and organised many of the party's election campaigns in the 1980s, at a time when the Liberal Party controlled the City Council. The first successful parliamentary by-election campaign he worked on was the [[1979 Liverpool Edge Hill by-election|Liverpool Edge Hill by-election]] in March 1979, at which the party's candidate was [[Lord Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]. Rennard was Alton's agent when he successfully contested the newly created [[Liverpool Mossley Hill (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Mossley Hill]] constituency in 1983 (after boundary changes) and helped to secure an excellent result there in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|a general election]] that saw a landslide [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] victory nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard, Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|accessdate=10 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Iain Dale interview with Lord Rennard |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml |title=Iain Dale interview with Lord Rennard |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219181245/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml |archivedate=19 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In conversation with... Chris Rennard|url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml|website=www.totalpolitics.com|publisher=Total Politics|accessdate=10 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219181245/http://www.totalpolitics.com/print/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml|archivedate=19 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984 he became one of the party's national Area Agents, based in [[Leicester]], when the party won its first seats there for over 20 years. He was a member of many of the Liberal/Alliance by-election campaign teams, including those in [[1986 West Derbyshire by-election|West Derbyshire in 1986]] and [[1987 Greenwich by-election|Greenwich in 1987]]. He was a member of the standing committee of ALC (Association of Liberal Councillors) and wrote some party publications on election campaigning and party organisation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Lord Rennard|url=http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=2340|website=www.liberal-international.org/|publisher=Liberal International|accessdate=10 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131122/http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=2340|archivedate=10 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==National positions==\nIn 1989 Rennard was appointed as Director of Campaigns and Elections for the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He married Ann McTegart<ref>{{cite web|author=The Peerage |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p31196.htm |title=The Peerage}}</ref> (whom he had met when they were both Liberal Party agents in Merseyside in the 1980s) and was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[1989 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51578 |date=31 December 1988 |page=15 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] he oversaw the party's target-seat campaign, which resulted in the Liberal Democrats nearly doubling its number of MPs from 26 to 46.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rennard and 50/50 hindsight|url=http://edinburgheye.wordpress.com/2014/01/27/rennard-and-5050-hindsight/|website=edinburgheye.wordpress.com|publisher=Edinburgh Eye|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=27 January 2014}}</ref> In 2001 and 2005, with Tim Razzall ([[Baron Razzall]]) as Campaign Chair and [[Charles Kennedy]] as Leader, he also directed the Liberal Democrats' general-election campaigns, which further increased the number of Lib Dem MPs respectively to 52 and 62, the largest total of Liberal or Liberal Democrat MPs since 1923.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Grady|first1=Sean|title=Chris Rennard: A Liberal Democrat who knows how to win elections|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-rennard-a-liberal-democrat-who-knows-how-to-win-elections-6271205.html|accessdate=18 November 2014|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rennard and 50/50 Hindsight|url=http://edinburgheye.wordpress.com/2014/01/27/rennard-and-5050-hindsight/|website=edinburgheye.wordpress.com|publisher=Edinburgh Eye|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was the party's Chief Executive between 2003 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-rennard/2484|website=www.parliament.uk/|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> During his employment by the Liberal Democrats at a national level, he was credited with winning 13 parliamentary by-elections for the party<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: low profile belied his influence on British politics|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/24/lord-rennard-lib-dems-profile|website=www.theguardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> (11 gains and 2 holds), out of a total of 74 by-elections held\u2014a success rate of 17.5%. The [[1990 Eastbourne by-election|Eastbourne by-election]] in 1990 was claimed by Rennard as rescuing the Liberal Democrats from their very weak position following the merger of the Liberal Party and the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]], and saw a 16,923 Conservative majority become a Liberal Democrat majority of 4,550.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|publisher=Lib dems|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> The by-election followed a major row between Rennard and [[Paddy Ashdown]] over the party leader\u2019s initial opposition to the Liberal Democrats fighting the by-election. A [[1993 Christchurch by-election|by-election in Christchurch during July 1993]] saw the Liberal Democrats gain the seat from the Conservatives by the largest swing (35%) against any British government since 1918.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/top-ten-lib-dem-breakthrough-moments/ |title=Top Ten Lib Dem 'breakthrough moments' |publisher=Epolitix.com |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512171830/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/top-ten-lib-dem-breakthrough-moments/ |archivedate=12 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard Baron Rennard of Wavertree|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|publisher=Lib Dems|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nFormer party leader Charles Kennedy has described Rennard as \"a quite extraordinary figure in British politics\", while his predecessor Paddy Ashdown praised Rennard as \"a formidable and widely-respected practitioner of political campaigning across all parties\".<ref>Paddy Ashdown, ''The Ashdown Diaries: Volume One, 1988-1997'' (Penguin, London, 2000) p.64</ref> [[Iain Dale]] said in an interview in ''[[Total Politics]]'' (June 2011) that Rennard \"is probably the most formidable and feared political campaigner of the last 20 years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.html |accessdate=14 June 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], [[Andrew Stunell]], a friend of Rennard's, is reported as having said: \"Last time people didn't follow Chris [Rennard's] instructions and the difference between those who did and who didn't&nbsp;\u2013 like in the [[Isle of Wight (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Wight]] [which the party lost]&nbsp;\u2013 was very clear. The message got through.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/08/uk.liberaldemocrats |author=Branigan, Tania |newspaper=The Guardian |location =London |date=8 April 2005 |title=Kennedy launches big push for 70-plus seats}}</ref>\n\nRennard has claimed credit for pioneering the successful Liberal Democrat election strategy of claiming narrow majorities when in second or even third place and ruthlessly squeezing third-party votes in Tory\u2013Lib Dem and Labour\u2013Lib Dem marginals; although this technique has been in use by the Liberal Party's campaigns teams since at least October 1974, when Rennard was 14 years old.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.markpack.org.uk/107519/first-tactical-voting-bar-chart-appear-political-leaflet/ |title = When did the first tactical voting bar chart appear on a political leaflet?|date = January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Later posts==\nRennard served as the Liberal Democrats Chief Executive from 2003 to 2009, during which time he was in overall charge of the party's election campaigns and organisation. His campaigns team continued to build the party's successes through by-elections such as [[2003 Brent East by-election|Brent East in 2003]] and [[2004 Leicester South by-election|Leicester South in 2004]]. Following the Lib Dems' victory at Brent East in 2003, ''[[The Independent]]'' profiled Lord Rennard, saying calling him \"a Liberal democrat who knows how to win elections\" and saying that \"In recent years thoughtful Conservatives surveying their wretched political predicament sometimes wondered aloud where \"their\" Peter Mandelson was. As usual they were asking the wrong question. They should have been seeking \"their\" Chris Rennard. For while Rennard enjoys a rather lower profile than New Labour's sultan of spin, the Liberal Democrats' own election guru is a no less formidable operator. True, Rennard has not managed to take the Liberal Democrats to Downing Street with a landslide majority, but it is in large part to him that the party owes its revival, the latest evidence of which was its victory in Brent East.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Rennard: A Liberal Democrat who knows how to win elections|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-rennard-a-liberal-democrat-who-knows-how-to-win-elections-6271205.html|website=www.independent.co.uk|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=20 September 2003}}</ref> As Chief Executive, Rennard oversaw the party\u2019s recovery from a series of crises in January 2006 when Charles Kennedy resigned as Leader, [[Mark Oaten]] resigned as the party\u2019s Home Affairs spokesman and [[Simon Hughes]] was claimed to be gay by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper. This turbulent period came to an end in March when he oversaw victory in the [[2006 Dunfermline and West Fife by-election]], which brought the total of Liberal Democrats MPs to 63.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly Information Bulletin: 23rd May 2009|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmwib/wb090523/state.htm|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> He chaired the Liberal Democrat general election campaign for both Sir [[Menzies Campbell]] and [[Nick Clegg]] between summer 2006 and May 2009, when he stood down as Chief Executive of the Party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Lord Rennard|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21569997|accessdate=18 November 2014|work=BBC News|date=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRennard announced that he would be standing down as chief executive of the Liberal Democrats in May 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/home/chris-rennard%E2%80%99s-personal-letter-to-members-265015275;show |title=Chris Rennard Personal Letter to Members |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527142916/http://www.libdems.org.uk/home/chris-rennard%E2%80%99s-personal-letter-to-members-265015275%3Bshow |archivedate=27 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He indicated that he had discussed standing down some time earlier with the party leader, Nick Clegg, and that this was for family and health reasons, saying that he had \"struggled to maintain good [[Diabetes|diabetic control]] with the rigours of a very demanding lifestyle\". Clegg subsequently conceded that sexual harassment allegations against Rennard from multiple women also contributed to Rennard's resignation, stating that \"He left on health grounds but of course the issues of his inappropriate behaviour were in the background.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Lord Rennard did not resign purely on health grounds, Clegg admits|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/27/lord-rennard-health-nick-clegg|website=www.theguardian.com/|accessdate=11 November 2015}}{{cite web|title=Profile: Sex claims contributed to Lord Rennard's resignation from Lib Dems, says Nick Clegg|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9897096/Sex-claims-contributed-to-Lord-Rennards-resignation-from-Lib-Dems-says-Nick-Clegg.html|website=www.telegraph.co.uk/|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter relinquishing the full-time position, Rennard continued to contribute to some party election campaigns on a constituency-by-constituency basis. However, Lib Dem President and future Party Leader [[Tim Farron]] insisted that \"Under no circumstances\" would Rennard have a future campaigning role.<ref>{{cite web|title=No role for Rennard, Farron tells accuser|url=https://www.politicshome.com/party-politics/articles/story/no-role-rennard-farron-tells-accuser|website=www.politicshome.com/|accessdate=11 November 2015|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> Rennard was appointed to chair a Commission on the [[Big Society]] set up by the [[Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations]] (ACEVO) to articulate a civil society vision of what charities wanted to achieve through the Big Society agenda. He was formerly a trustee of the charity [[Action on Smoking and Health]] (ASH).\n\nHe is a Patron of The Crescent, a centre in [[St Albans]] which provides help and support to those living with, or otherwise affected by, [[HIV]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.thecrescent.org.uk/index.php/about/|website=www.thecrescent.org.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nLord Rennard provides advice and support on campaign, communication, fundraising and management issues through the consultancy Rennard & McTegart Ltd. He is the Director of Communications for the British Healthcare Trades Association (BHTA) and writes a regular \"Westminster Watch\" column for their Bulletin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Westminster Watch|url=http://www.bhta.net/westminsterwatch|website=www.bhta.net/|accessdate=18 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129052229/http://www.bhta.net/westminsterwatch|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nRennard was created a [[life peer]] on 21 July 1999 as Baron Rennard, of [[Wavertree]] in the [[Merseyside|County of Merseyside]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55564 |date=27 July 1999 |page=8076}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 27 July 1999.<ref>{{cite web|author=Minute Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/minutes/990727/ldminute.htm |title=House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings, 27 July 1999 |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> He is the treasurer of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Diabetes and a vice chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Smoking and Health.{{fact|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn the House of Lords, Rennard has mostly spoken on political and constitutional reform issues. He led for the Liberal Democrats in debate on what became the [[Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000]], that set the framework for rules such as those governing party finance. He spoke in favour of replacing large donor funding of parties, with limited state funding. He has campaigned against abuses of the postal vote system and helped to bring about some reforms to it. He has spoken out strongly for and voted for [[reform of the House of Lords]] at every possible stage. In the 2010\u20132015 Parliament he was responsible for changing proposals to move electoral registration to an entirely voluntary system that some say would have greatly favoured the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile Chris Rennard|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/chris_rennard|website=www.libdems.org.uk|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> He was also responsible in the House of Lords for the cross-party amendment that blocked [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|the proposed review of parliamentary boundaries]], thought by some to favour the Conservatives by up to 30 seats at the next general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201213/ldhansrd/text/130114-0001.htm#1301145000174)|website=publications.parliament.uk|title= Hansard House of Lords Monday, 14 January 2013|publisher=Hansard|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> He also speaks in the Lords on other issues, including some associated with public health including diabetes and smoking.\n\n===Expenses===\nIn May 2009 Rennard was criticised for claiming a House of Lords member\u2019s allowance of \u00a341,678, having designated a flat in Eastbourne as his main residence and his central London house as his second home.<ref name=expenses>{{cite news|title= LDV Members' Survey \u2013 MPs' expenses (1): what you said about Chris Rennard |url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/ldv-members-survey-mps-expenses-1-what-you-said-about-chris-rennard-14901.html|work=[[Stephen Tall]]|publisher= Liberal Democrat Voice |date=21 May 2005}}</ref> A subsequent complaint made by the Sunlight Centre for Open Politics was investigated by the Clerk of the Parliaments [[Michael Pownall]], who did not uphold it, \"In view of the assurances by Lord Rennard about the change in his circumstances and the time he spends in Eastbourne, and in the absence of any definition of main address in the current guidance to the House of Lords\u2019 Members Expenses Scheme\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/upload/LordRennardcomplaint.pdf|title=Complaint against Lord Rennard|date=20 October 2009|website=www.parliament.uk|publisher=House of Lords|accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of sexual harassment==\nIn February 2013, ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' ran a report on Lord Rennard, alleging a history of sexual harassment during his time as an official of the party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Cathy|title=Lib Dems allegations of sexual impropriety  |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/lib-dem-allegations-of-sexual-impropriety|publisher=Channel 4 News / Firecrest Films |accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> Channel 4 stated that the alleged victims decided to comment publicly since Rennard had begun to again play an 'active role in the Party'.<ref name=activerole>{{cite news|title= Lord Rennard: why are we running the story now? |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/lord-rennard-why-are-we-running-the-story-now|accessdate=11 November 2015|work=[[Cathy Newman]]|publisher= Channel 4 News |date=25 February 2013}}</ref> He strongly denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Rennard issues fresh denial of sexual impropriety claims|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21543152|work=BBC News|date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest claims go back to 2007 when two women met [[Paul Burstow]], then the party's Chief Whip in the Commons, to raise the issue with him.<ref>Rowena Mason [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10116934/Nick-Clegg-admits-he-knew-of-Lord-Rennard-rumours-for-years.html \"Timelime of the Lord Rennard sexual harassment allegations\"], telegraph.co.uk, 12 June 2013</ref> In a February 2013 statement issued shortly after ''Channel 4 News'' had broken the story, Nick Clegg wrote that claims about the improper conduct of Lord Rennard had been brought to his attention in 2008, but Rennard had denied any wrongdoing when challenged.<ref name=\"C4240213\">[http://www.channel4.com/news/clegg-aware-of-concerns-about-lord-rennard \"Clegg aware of 'concerns' about Lord Rennard\"], ''Channel 4 News'', 24 February 2013</ref> The \"indirect and non-specific concerns\" he had been told about meant that he could take no further action,<ref name=\"C4240213\"/> but [[Danny Alexander]], Clegg's chief of staff at the time, had warned Rennard that the alleged behaviour would be \"wholly unacceptable\".<ref>Juliette Jowit and Steven Morris [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/24/nick-clegg-admits-rennard-concerns \"Nick Clegg admits he heard of Rennard 'concerns' in 2008\"], ''The Guardian'', 24 February 2013</ref> A subsequent independent report in June 2013 by Helena Morrissey into \"processes and culture within the Liberal Democrats\" said that the leadership should have held an inquiry into the allegations at that time (when Rennard was still a member of staff).<ref>Rowena Mason [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10116359/Nick-Clegg-admits-he-knew-of-Lord-Rennard-rumours-for-years.html \"Nick Clegg 'should have ordered Rennard sex harassment inquiry after 2008 warnings'\"], telegraph.co.uk, 12 June 2013</ref>\n\nThere was no such inquiry until that conducted by Alistair Webster QC, who concluded after examining over a hundred statements (including those made by the complainants as a result of interviews with specially trained police officers) that the evidence was insufficient to proceed to a disciplinary hearing. While staffing disciplinary matters would have required a civil standard of proof to be met, at that time Liberal Democrat regulations demanded a criminal standard of proof to uphold allegations against a Party member.\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police]] carried out their own investigation after one of the complainants went to them on 27 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1082051/met-police-formally-investigate-lord-rennard|title=Met Police Formally Investigate Lord Rennard|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 April 2013 |website=news.sky.com |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> On 26 September 2013 the Metropolitan Police announced they had dropped the investigation, because they had found \"insufficient evidence\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|title=Police drop Lord Rennard sexual misconduct inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/26/police-drop-lord-rennard-inquiry|accessdate=27 September 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 September 2013}}</ref> They did not submit a file to the Crown Prosecution Service for consideration.<ref>{{cite web|title=Police drop Lord Rennard sexual misconduct inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/26/police-drop-lord-rennard-inquiry|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the police \"No Further Action\" decision, the Liberal Democrats resumed their own inquiry with Alistair Webster QC acting as \"independent investigator.\" According to a later public statement by Lord Rennard, there were three complaints by the deadline of 22 November 2013, and Alistair Webster reported that there was insufficient evidence to proceed further.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: His statement in full|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lord-rennard-his-statement-in-full-9073125.html|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref> A fourth complaint was then also considered and Alistair Webster again reported (on 22 December 2013) that there was insufficient evidence to proceed any further. The party rules required the independent QC to either recommend a disciplinary hearing to investigate further, or to say that there was insufficient evidence to proceed.\n\nAlistair Webster informed Lord Rennard on 15 January 2014 that the decision was \"No Further Action\", and that the party statement that day was \"not his responsibility.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard: Hos Statement in Full|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lord-rennard-his-statement-in-full-9073125.html|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref>  Webster's public statement on his conclusions from his report stated that there was \"broadly credible\" evidence of \"behaviour which violated the personal space and autonomy of the complainants.\"<ref name=Webster>{{cite news|title= Internal investigation into allegations against Lord Rennard |url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/internal-investigation-into-allegations-against-lord-rennard-37847.html| publisher= Lib Dem Voice |date=15 Jan 2014}}</ref> The question of the standard of proof required did not arise as the evidence was insufficient to hold a disciplinary hearing - except that Webster did consider this question, noting in his statement that \"my task was to review the evidence which I received and consider whether there was a greater than 50% chance that such a charge could be proved to the standard required by the rules, i.e. proof beyond reasonable doubt [a criminal, rather than civil standard of proof] ... My view, judging the evidence as a whole, is that there is a less than 50% chance that a charge against Lord Rennard could be proved to the requisite standard\". Webster concluded that it was \"unlikely that it could be established beyond reasonable doubt that Lord Rennard had intended to act in an indecent or sexually inappropriate way\" and that \"I have specifically discounted suggestions made during the investigation that the incidents had been invented as part of a political campaign against Lord Rennard. In my view Lord Rennard ought to reflect upon the effect that his behaviour has had and the distress which it caused and that an apology would be appropriate, as would a commitment to change his behaviour in future\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lib Dems will take no action against Lord Rennard over harassment claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jan/15/lord-rennard-lib-dems-no-action-sex-pest-complaints|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nNeither Nick Clegg nor Tim Farron had read the Webster report (Webster stated 'I do not consider it appropriate to publish the evidence') and Lord Rennard was initially also denied sight of it, in spite of earlier promises that he would see it.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard gets Lib Dem apology for botched disciplinary process|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/25/lord-rennard-lib-dem-apology-disciplinary-process|website=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Farron asked Lord Rennard to apologise to the women involved. It was reported in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that Clegg had stated that \"it is right that Chris Rennard has been asked in this report to apologise, to reflect on his behaviour.\" Clegg went on to state that Rennard would not be \"playing any role in my general election plans for the campaign in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=POLITICS: Lord Rennard allegations: Nick Clegg interview on independent report|url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist//ITN/2014/01/15/R15011408/?v=1|website=www.itnsource.com}}</ref>\n\nThe report was eventually provided to Lord Rennard and to the four complainants in March 2014 and it did not contain any request or recommendation for an apology [citation needed] - though Webster made this request in his Jan 2014 public statement on conclusions from his investigation.<ref name=\"Webster\"/> A statement from Lord Rennard in August 2014 said that a Liberal Democrat English Appeals Committee ruling in July 2014 found that \"I could not be criticised over my reaction to the previous report by Alistair Webster QC, as I was not given sight of the report for 11 weeks\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard's Liberal Democrat suspension is lifted|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-08-19/lord-rennard-statement-in-full/|website=www.itv.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2014, Rennard was suspended from the Liberal Democrats; he was informed that this was on the basis of \"Media and social media comments made by you, endorsed by you and made on your behalf that have attacked the party and the party processes publicly since the announcement of the Webster report results.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard Has Lib Dem Suspension Lifted|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/08/19/lord-rennard-has-lib-dem-suspension-lifted_n_5692668.html|website=www.huffingtonpost.co.uk}}</ref> Lord Rennard's friend and legal adviser, [[Lord Carlile of Berriew|Lord Carlile]], wrote a strongly critical article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' about \"the party's unjust and arbitrary conduct of the case\".<ref name=les>{{cite news|title=Former aide to Nick Clegg quits the Lib-Dems over Lord Rennard row|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/former-aide-to-nick-clegg-quits-the-libdems-over-lord-rennard-row-9070194.html|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|publisher=Evening Standard Ltd|date=19 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=beebunjust>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Victoria|title=Savile claims and royal 'job-share' - newspaper review|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-the-papers-25797931|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[BBC]]|date=19 January 2014}}</ref> The week following the suspension, ''[[The Times]]'' reported<ref name=cuban>{{cite news|title= Rennard could expose Lib Dem sex scandals |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article1367820.ece|accessdate=11 November 2015|work=[[The Times]]|publisher= Times Newspapers Limited |date=26 January 2014}}</ref> from 'allies' of Rennard that the peer knew \"where the bodies are buried\" and that were he expelled from the Liberal Democrats he would reveal two decades of sex scandal in the Party: \"We have had a [[Cuban missile crisis]] over the past week.\"\n\nLord Rennard issued a lengthy personal statement in response to his suspension explaining some of the background to the allegations made against him and the party's handling of them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard statement in full|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25814565|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe seven-month suspension of his party membership was lifted in August 2014, when there was a \"No Further Action\" decision in relation to his criticisms of party processes and he was restored to full membership of the party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Rennard has suspension from Lib Dems lifted|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28858533|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref> A later statement was issued by Rennard on 21 August 2014 saying that:\n{{cquote|All allegations made about Lord Rennard have now been investigated thoroughly. This included a seven month investigation by specially trained officers of the Metropolitan Police. The police decided that there could be no charges and did not even a send a file to the Crown Prosecution Service. In addition, there was a lengthy investigation by independent QC Alistair Webster. He also concluded that there was insufficient evidence even to proceed to a disciplinary hearing. The Liberal Democrat Party has now dealt with all the allegations and the matter is closed. We must advise anyone against publishing or broadcasting defamatory remarks. Accusations that were rejected by both the Metropolitan Police and an independent QC would be treated as such.<ref name = \"LD Voice\">[http://libdemvoice.org/statement-from-lord-rennard-42120.html Statement from Lord Rennard Liberal Democrat Voice, 21 August 2014 Accessed 22 August 2014]</ref>}}\n\nHelena Morrissey was invited to report on processes and culture within the Liberal Democrats, and her report in December 2014 concluded, in relation to Lord Rennard, that:\n\n{{cquote|At this point, December 2014, every investigation has concluded with no further action to be taken against Lord Rennard. The process over the past nearly two years \u2013 conducted according to the prevailing rules \u2013 has run its course and although the outcome is a source of great frustration to some, I believe that the Party can only move on if that outcome is accepted. At this stage, given that the Party applied its own processes, there is no justification for it remaining ambivalent towards Lord Rennard \u2013 he should be just as welcome a participant or guest at Party events as any other.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morrissey|first1=Helena|title=Progress Report on the Processes and Culture of the Liberal Democrats|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/libdems/pages/7117/attachments/original/1418903950/M-report-part-2.pdf?1418903950|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>}} She also observed how the Party's burden of proof for disciplinary procedures had been lowered from a criminal ('beyond reasonable doubt') to a civil standard of proof ('on the balance of probabilities').\n\nDuring his campaign to become Liberal Democrat leader, Tim Farron said that if elected he would have \"no intention of appointing him [Rennard] to any role in the party.\"<ref name=farron>{{cite news|title= Rennard could expose Lib Dem sex scandals\n |url=http://www.markpack.org.uk/133285/what-role-would-rennard-have-under-a-new-lib-dem-leader/|work=[[Mark Pack]]|publisher= Mark Pack |date=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, the Party's Deputy Leader (and future Leader), [[Jo Swinson]], expressed her desire in a comment piece that Lord Rennard would not be a Liberal Democrat member, writing \"That Lord Rennard remains in the party, showing no remorse or contrition, while many of the women involved have left, fills me with sadness and anger ... I do not want Lord Rennard to continue as a member of the party. As far as I am concerned, he is not welcome.\"<ref name=SwinsonsaysRennardnotwelcome>{{cite news|title= Sexual harassment: a chance for change |url= https://medium.com/@jo_swinson/sexual-harassment-a-chance-for-change-1e87a9db1581| publisher= Medium |date=19 Nov 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attempt to join Liberal Democrat Federal Executive==\nIn November 2015 Rennard was chosen to serve as the Liberal Democrat Lords' representative to the Liberal Democrats' governing Federal Executive Committee. A Special Conference triggered by Party members opposed to the decision was averted when Rennard agreed to resign his Committee membership following a public intervention by Tim Farron, who stated \"Chris serving on the FE is not in our best interest, as the levels of anger and division have shown. I am therefore asking Chris to step down from the FE in the best interests of the party\".<ref name=Farronpubliccall>{{cite news|title= Tim Farron calls on Chris Rennard to step down from the Federal Executive |url= http://www.libdemvoice.org/breaking-tim-farron-calls-on-chris-rennard-to-step-down-from-the-federal-executive-48283.html| publisher= Lib Dem Voice |date=17 Nov 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Memoirs==\nThe first volume of his memoirs, ''Winning Here'', went on sale on 25 January 2018.<ref>Private Eye issue No 1463 - 9\u201322 February 2018 - Page 11 \"Comeuppance Corner\"</ref>\nThe launch was mired in controversy, when it turned out Lord Rennard was being investigated by the information commissioner for a breach of data protection law by sending unsolicited emails promoting the book to Lib Dem supporters. ''[[Private Eye]]'' reported that the email offered a 25% discount \"when you click through to the shopping page\". Readers who accepted would then be treated to how \"I started running council elections in my teens, was a successful constituent agent at 22, the Lib Dem director of campaigns and elections at 29, a peer at 39\". ''Private Eye'' titled the article \"Comeuppance Corner\", as Lord Rennard was one of those that voted for a change in the data protection law to make newspapers pay both sides' costs in data protection cases.<ref>Biteback Publishing (25 Jan. 2018) {{ISBN|1785903373}} {{ISBN|978-1785903373}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,,1263235,00.html Profile] From ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 2004.\n*Interview with Lord Rennard [https://web.archive.org/web/20120311174423/http://www.thirdsector.co.uk/News/Article/1052871/Interview-Lord-Rennard-chair-Acevos-Big-Society-Commission] From ''[[Third Sector (magazine)|Third Sector]]'' February 2011\n*Article on the AV Referendum [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/14/av-miliband-clegg] From ''[[The Guardian]]'' March 2011\n*In depth interview with Lord Rennard for ''Civil Society'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20110418065050/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/finance/indepth/interviews/content/8683/liberal_influence_andrew_hind_interviews_lord_rennard]\n*In conversation with Iain Dale for Total Politics [https://web.archive.org/web/20110613024904/http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/160427/in-conversation-with-chris-rennard.thtml] June 2011\n*Lord Rennard's article about the Big Society [http://www.libdemvoice.org/chris-rennard-fill-in-the-blanks-of-the-big-society-24266.html] June 2011\n*The They Work For You website [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/lord_rennard]\n\n{{Current Liberal Democrat Peers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rennard, Chris}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Liverpool Blue Coat School]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Rennard,_Baron_Rennard"}
{"title_page": "Monroe Palmer, Baron Palmer of Childs Hill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox office holder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Palmer of Child's Hill\n|honorific-suffix = [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Palmer of Childs Hill crop 2, 2019.jpg\n|office           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start       = 17 January 2011<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end         = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1938|11|30|df=y}}\n|occupation       = Politician\n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|alma_mater       = \n}}\n'''Monroe Edward Palmer, Baron Palmer of Child's Hill''', [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] (born 30 November 1938)<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/90429.stm|title=Lord Palmer of Childs Hill | work=[[BBC News]] | publisher=[[BBC]] | location=UK }}</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician and [[life peer]] in the [[House of Lords]].\n\nBorn on 30 November 1938, Palmer was [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] treasurer between 1971\u201383.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> He was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1982 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=48837 |date=31 December 1981 |page=11 }}</ref> He contested the [[Hendon South]] constituency at the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]], [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] general elections for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] party, and was joint treasurer of the [[Liberal parliamentary party]] from 1977\u201383. Following the creation of the Liberal Democrats he contested [[Hastings and Rye]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] and [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] general elections.\n\nPalmer was a [[Barnet London Borough Council|Barnet councillor]] in [[Childs Hill]] first elected 1986,retired 2014, and was Chair of its [[Audit Committee]] of a Council with a \u00a3500 million net annual expenditure. On 19 November 2010, it was announced that Palmer would be created a [[life peer]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/latest-news/2010/11/peerages-honours-and-appointments-2-57256| title = Latest Peerages announced - 10 Downing Street| accessdate = 13 February 2011}}</ref> He was created '''Baron Palmer of Childs Hill''', of [[Childs Hill]] in the [[London Borough of Barnet]] on 17 January 2011<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59676 |date=20 January 2011 |page=870}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-palmer-of-childs-hill/4214|publisher=UK Parliament|title=Lord Palmer of Childs Hill|date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=13 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\nMonroe Palmer is a [[Chartered Accountant]] and a former Senior Partner in General Practice.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nIn the House of Lords, Palmer spoke, until May 2014, on defence (procurement, housing, veterans) and now{{when|date=January 2016}} speaks on international affairs, local government, taxation, fire and safety, and all matters relating to trade and business.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} He has a long-standing interest in achieving peace in the [[Middle East]] and is a regular speaker on this and also on matters of concern to the [[UK Jewish Community]]. Palmer is a Vice President of the [[Jewish Leadership Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejlc.org/vice_presidents|title=Vice Presidents|accessdate=2 September 2019|work=Jewish Leadership Council}}</ref>\n\nPalmer is married to Susette (who has written a book on knitting and lectures on cruise liners);{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} he has three children and seven grandchildren including \"up and coming rap artist\" Dave in Charge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daveincharge.com/|title=Dave in Charge|publisher=Dave In Charge |date=2014|accessdate=13 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Treasurer of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]|years=1977 \u2013 1983|before=[[Philip Watkins]]|with=[[Rhys Lloyd, Baron Lloyd of Kilgerran|Rhys Lloyd]]|after=[[Wynn Normington Hugh-Jones]]<br/>[[Anthony Jacobs]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Current Liberal Democrat Peers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palmer, Monroe, Baron Palmer Of Childs Hill}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English accountants]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox office holder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Palmer of Child's Hill\n|honorific-suffix = [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Palmer of Childs Hill crop 2, 2019.jpg\n|office           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start       = 17 January 2011<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end         = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1938|11|30|df=y}}\n|occupation       = Politician\n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|alma_mater       = \n}}\n'''Monroe Edward Palmer, Baron Palmer of Child's Hill''', [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] (born 30 November 1938)<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/90429.stm|title=Lord Palmer of Childs Hill | work=[[BBC News]] | publisher=[[BBC]] | location=UK }}</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician and [[life peer]] in the [[House of Lords]].\n\nBorn on 30 November 1938, Palmer was [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] treasurer between 1971\u201383.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> He was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1982 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=48837 |date=31 December 1981 |page=11 }}</ref> He contested the [[Hendon South]] constituency at the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]], [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] general elections for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] party, and was joint treasurer of the [[Liberal parliamentary party]] from 1977-83. Following the creation of the Liberal Democrats he contested [[Hastings and Rye]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] and [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] general elections.\n\nPalmer was a [[Barnet London Borough Council|Barnet councillor]] in [[Childs Hill]] first elected 1986,retired 2014, and was Chair of its [[Audit Committee]] of a Council with a \u00a3500 million net annual expenditure. On 19 November 2010, it was announced that Palmer would be created a [[life peer]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/latest-news/2010/11/peerages-honours-and-appointments-2-57256| title = Latest Peerages announced - 10 Downing Street| accessdate = 13 February 2011}}</ref> He was created '''Baron Palmer of Childs Hill''', of [[Childs Hill]] in the [[London Borough of Barnet]] on 17 January 2011<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59676 |date=20 January 2011 |page=870}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-palmer-of-childs-hill/4214|publisher=UK Parliament|title=Lord Palmer of Childs Hill|date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=13 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\nMonroe Palmer is a [[Chartered Accountant]] and a former Senior Partner in General Practice.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nIn the House of Lords, Palmer spoke, until May 2014, on defence (procurement, housing, veterans) and now{{when|date=January 2016}} speaks on international affairs, local government, taxation, fire and safety, and all matters relating to trade and business.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} He has a long-standing interest in achieving peace in the [[Middle East]] and is a regular speaker on this and also on matters of concern to the [[UK Jewish Community]]. Palmer is a Vice President of the [[Jewish Leadership Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejlc.org/vice_presidents|title=Vice Presidents|accessdate=2 September 2019|work=Jewish Leadership Council}}</ref>\n\nPalmer is married to Susette (who has written a book on knitting and lectures on cruise liners);{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} he has three children and seven grandchildren including \"up and coming rap artist\" Dave in Charge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daveincharge.com/|title=Dave in Charge|publisher=Dave In Charge |date=2014|accessdate=13 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Treasurer of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]|years=1977 \u2013 1983|before=[[Philip Watkins]]|with=[[Rhys Lloyd, Baron Lloyd of Kilgerran|Rhys Lloyd]]|after=[[Wynn Normington Hugh-Jones]]<br/>[[Anthony Jacobs]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Current Liberal Democrat Peers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palmer, Monroe, Baron Palmer Of Childs Hill}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English accountants]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1977-83 \u2192 1977\u201383", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monroe_Palmer,_Baron_Palmer_of_Childs_Hill"}
